[[File:Cajero Banelco.jpg|thumb|Client using a Banelco ATM in Buenos Aires]] '''Banelco''' (an acronym for '''''Ban'''ca '''El'''ectrónica '''Co'''mpartida'') is an [[Automated teller machine|ATM]] network in [[Argentina]]. Established in 1985, it offers several services related to cash flow management, including [[debit card]]s, electronic transfers and service payments.
Banelco is owned by private banks and operates 6.000 ATMs (one third of the total in the country).<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.aba-argentina.com/informes/ranking_bancos/PDF/2011/RankingAbril2011.xls|title=Ranking del sistema financiero|publisher=ABA|access-date=2011-12-11|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20120426044416/http://www.aba-argentina.com/informes/ranking_bancos/PDF/2011/RankingAbril2011.xls|archive-date=2012-04-26|dead-url=yes|df=}}</ref> Its main competitor in the Argentine market is [[Red Link (ATM)|Red Link]]. The company also operates Pagomiscuentas, an [[electronic bill payment]] service.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.banelco.com/LaEmpresa/Default.aspx|title=La Empresa|publisher=Banelco, S.A|access-date=2011-12-11|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20111223110453/http://www.banelco.com/LaEmpresa/Default.aspx|archive-date=2011-12-23|dead-url=yes|df=}}</ref>
==Member banks== Banks in Argentina which maintain Banelco ATMs include: * Banco Comafi * Banco del Sol * [[Banco Galicia]] * [[Banco Itaú]] * [[Banco Macro]] * [[Banco Patagonia]] * Banco Regional del Cuyo * [[Banco Santander Río]] * Banco Supervielle * [[BBVA Banco Francés]] * [[Citibank Argentina|Citi Bank]] * [[HSBC Bank Argentina|HSBC Argentina]] * [[Industrial and Commercial Bank of China|ICBC Bank]] * BRJFO AMUR
